      "\n     - For `k₁ = 1, k₂ = 3`, `gcd(3⁹ - 3, 2³ - 3) = gcd(3⁹ - 3, 5)` and `3⁹ = 19683 ≡ 1⁹ = 1 mod 5`, so `3⁹ - 3 ≡ -2 ≡ 3 mod 5`, and `3⁹ - 3 = 19680`, `gcd(19680, 5) = 5`, but `p` could be `5`. However, `2³ - 3 = 5`, and `3⁹ - 3 = 19680 = 5 * 3936`, so `p = 5` divides both `2^{3¹} - 3 = 5` and `2^{3²} - 3 = 512 - 3 = 509`, `509 / 5 ≈ 101.8`, and `509 = 5·101 + 4`, so `509 mod 5 = 4`. Oh no, my earlier calculation of `2^{3²} - 3 = 512 - 3 = 509`, `3⁹ - 3 = 19683 - 3 = 19680`, but `509 mod 5 = 4`, and `19680 ≡ 0 mod 5`. Hence, my assumption that `2^{3^{k₁}} ≡ 3` and `2^{3^{k₂}} ≡ 3` would imply `3^{3^{k₂ - k₁}} ≡ 3 mod p` was wrong because `(2^{3^{k₁}})^{3^{k₂ - k₁}} ≡ 3^{3^{k₂ - k₁}} mod p`, but `2^{3^{k₁}·3^{k₂ - k₁}} = 2^{3^{k₂}} ≡ 3 mod p`, so `3^{3^{k₂ - k₁}} ≡ 3 mod p`, and we have `p` divides `3^{3^{k₂ - k₁}} - 3` and `p` divides `2^{3^{k₁}} - 3`. \n\n   The case `k₁ = 1, k₂ = 2` seems fine (`p = 1` is the only one). \n   What about `k₁ = 2, k₂ = 3`? We have `2⁹ - 3 = 512 - 3 = 509` and `2²⁷ - 3 = 134217728 - 3 = 134217725`. The gcd of 509 and 134217725 is `gcd(509, 134217725)` and `509 * 263788 = 509 * 263788 ≈ 1.34e5 ≈ 134200000`:\n     - `509 * 263788 = 509 * (250000 + 13788) = 127250000 + 509 * 13788 ≈ 1.27e8 + 510 * 14000 ≈ 1.27e8 + 7.14e6 ≈ 1.3414e8. 509 * 13788 = 509 * 14000 - 509 * 212 ≈ 7,126,000 - 108,000 ≈ 7,018,000`, and `509 * 263788 ≈ 127,250,000 + 7,018,000 ≈ 134,268,000`, and `134217725 - 134268000 ≈ -50000`. Hmm, perhaps `509 * 263788 = 134,268,092`, but `134,217,725 + 50,367 = 134,268,092` → difference is `50,367`. So the actual gcd is checking `gcd(509, 50367)`, then `50367 mod 509 = 50367 - 98 * 509 = 50367 - 50382 = -15`, so no, 509 does not divide 134217725? \n\n   Actually, checking: 134217725 / 509 ≈ 263,788.64 → 509 * 263788 = 134268092, and `134268092 - 134217725 = 50367`, so 134217725 ≡ -50367 mod 509, `gcd(509, 50367)`. Repeat:\n   - 50367 / 509 ≈ 98.95 → 509 * 98 = 49882, remainder 50367 - 49882 = 485. Now `gcd(509, 485)` → 509 - 485 = 24, `gcd(485, 24)` → 485 mod 24 = 5 (24 * 20 = 480), so `gcd(24, 5) = 1`. \n\n   So `gcd(509, 134217725) = 1`, and thus no prime",
