      "\n   No! For example, `n=2 → 1`, `n=4 → 13`, `n=8 → 253 = 11·23`. But we already saw that `2⁴ - 3 = 13` and `2⁸ - 3 = 253` have gcd `13`. Hence, not all pairs are coprime. \n\n   **Mistake:** It seems that choosing `n=4` and `n=8` violates the condition, because `gcd(13, 253) = 13`. \n\n   **Revised Idea:** The initial idea was too naive. A better approach is to note that for any `m`, if we consider numbers of the form `2^(m·k + 1) - 3`, they might have some special property. But perhaps not. \n\n   Alternatively, note that if we can find an infinite set of numbers of the form `2ⁿ - 3` such that no two share a common prime factor. \n\n   **Solution Attempt:**  \n   Consider the sequence of numbers `a_k = 2^(2k) - 3`. Then, for `k = 1`, `a_1 = 1`; for `k = 2`, `a_2 = 13`; for `k = 3`, `a_3 = 61`; etc. \n   - We observe that `a_1 = 1`, so any pair including `a_1` is trivially coprime. \n   - But as shown, `a_2 = 13` and `a_4 = 65533` have a common factor of `13`, so not every pair is coprime. \n\n   **Final Solution:**  \n   Instead of choosing exponents `2k`, let’s try exponents that are powers of `2`. Define `a_k = 2^(2ᵏ) - 3`, for `k ≥ 1`. \n   - `a_1 = 1`, `a_2 = 13`, `a_3 = 253`, etc. \n   However, as observed, `a_2 = 13` and `a_4 = 2¹⁶ - 3 = 65533 = 13·5041`, so they share a common factor of `13`. \n\n   **New Idea:** Take exponents that are primes, but larger. Maybe take `a_p = 2^p - 3` for primes `p ≥ 5`. However, `a_5 = 29`, `a_7 = 125`, and `gcd(29, 125) = 1`, but `a_5 = 29`, `a_{11}` is `2045 = 5·409`, and `gcd(29, 2045)`? `2045 / 29 ≈ 70.5`, no. Maybe it's `1`. \n\n   It seems hard to guarantee coprimality this way. \n\n   **Alternative Insight:** Note that we can consider the sequence `a_k = 2^(k + 2) - 3`, for `k ≥ 0`. The first few terms are `1, 5, 13, 29, 61, ...`. Checking:\n   - `gcd(1, 5) = 1`, `gcd(1, 13) = 1`, etc. \n   - `gcd(5, 13) = 1`, `gcd(5, 29)`? Since `29 ≡ 4 mod 5`, no. In fact, `gcd(5, 29) = 1`. \n   - `gcd(13, 29)`? `29 ≡ 3 mod 13`, no: `gcd(13, 29) = 1`.  \n   - But what about `gcd(5, 61)`? `61 ≡ 1 mod 5`, so `gcd(5, 61) = 1`. \n\n   Hmm",
      "1",
      "too complicated to formalize. \n\n**Alternative Concrete Approach:**\nConsider the set `S = {2^{n!} - 3 | n ∈ ℕ, n ≥ 2}`. \n\nBut for `n=2`: `2^{2} - 3 = 1`\n`n=3`: `2^{6} - 3 = 61`\n`n=4`: `2^{24} - 3` which is big. \n\nBut does it work? Check `n=2`, `m=3`: `gcd(1,61)=1`. `n=3`, `m=4`:",
      "\n  have h_main : ∃ (s : Set ℕ+), s.Infinite ∧ s.Pairwise fun m n => Nat.Coprime (2 ^ n.val - 3) (2 ^ m.val - 3) := by\n    use Set.range fun n : ℕ+ => ⟨(2 * n : ℕ) + 1, by\n      simp [PNat.mk_coe, Nat.add_assoc, Nat.add_pos_right]\n      <;> norm_cast <;>\n      (try decide) <;>\n      (try\n        {\n          cases n\n          · simp_all [PNat]\n          · simp_all [PNat, Nat.mul_succ]\n          <;> omega\n        })\n      ⟩\n    constructor\n    · -- Prove that the set is infinite\n      have h₁ : Set.Infinite (Set.range fun n : ℕ+ => ⟨(2 * n : ℕ) + 1, by\n        simp [PNat.mk_coe, Nat.add_assoc, Nat.add_pos_right]\n        <;> norm_cast <;>\n        (try decide) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            cases n\n            · simp_all [PNat]\n            · simp_all [PNat, Nat.mul_succ]\n            <;> omega\n          })\n        ⟩) := by\n        have h₂ : Function.Injective fun n : ℕ+ => ⟨(2 * n : ℕ) + 1, by\n          simp [PNat.mk_coe, Nat.add_assoc, Nat.add_pos_right]\n          <;> norm_cast <;>\n          (try decide) <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              cases n\n              · simp_all [PNat]\n              · simp_all [PNat, Nat.mul_succ]\n              <;> omega\n            })\n          ⟩ := by\n          intro n m h\n          simp [PNat.ext_iff] at h\n          <;>\n          (try cases n <;> cases m <;> simp_all [PNat, Nat.mul_add, Nat.add_mul, Nat.mul_one, Nat.mul_zero] <;> ring_nf at * <;> omega)\n          <;>\n          (try omega)\n          <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              norm_cast at *\n              <;> omega\n            })\n          <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              simp_all [PNat]\n              <;> omega\n            })\n        exact Set.infinite_range_of_injective h₂\n      exact h₁\n    · -- Prove that every pair of elements in the set is coprime\n      refine' Set.Pairwise.mono _ (Set.pairwise_range _)\n      intro m n h\n      simp_all [Set.mem_range]\n      <;>\n      (try\n        {\n          rcases m with ⟨m, hm⟩\n          rcases n with ⟨n, hn⟩\n          simp_all [PNat.mk_coe]\n          <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              have h₁ : Nat.Coprime (2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) (2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) := by\n                have h₂ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) % 3 = 2 := by\n                  have h₃ : ∀ k : ℕ, 2 ^ (2 * k + 1) % 3 = 2 := by\n                    intro k\n                    induction k with\n                    | zero => norm_num\n                    | succ k ih =>\n                      simp [pow_add, pow_mul, Nat.mul_mod, Nat.pow_mod, ih]\n                      <;> norm_num <;> omega\n                  have h₄ := h₃ n\n                  simpa using h₄\n                have h₃ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) % 3 = 2 := by\n                  have h₄ : ∀ k : ℕ, 2 ^ (2 * k + 1) % 3 = 2 := by\n                    intro k\n                    induction k with\n                    | zero => norm_num\n                    | succ k ih =>\n                      simp [pow_add, pow_mul, Nat.mul_mod, Nat.pow_mod, ih]\n                      <;> norm_num <;> omega\n                  have h₅ := h₄ m\n                  simpa using h₅\n                have h₄ : (2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) % 3 = 2 := by\n                  omega\n                have h₅ : (2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) % 3 = 2 := by\n                  omega\n                have h₆ : Nat.Coprime (2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) (2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) := by\n                  -- Use the fact that both numbers are congruent to 2 modulo 3 to show they are coprime\n                  have h₇ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3 > 0 := by\n                    have h₈ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) > 3 := by\n                      have h₉ : 2 * n + 1 ≥ 3 := by\n                        have h₁₀ : n ≥ 1 := by\n                          omega\n                        omega\n                      have h₁₀ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) ≥ 2 ^ 3 := by\n                        exact pow_le_pow_right (by norm_num) (by omega)\n                      omega\n                    omega\n                  have h₈ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3 > 0 := by\n                    have h₉ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) > 3 := by\n                      have h₁₀ : 2 * m + 1 ≥ 3 := by\n                        have h₁₁ : m ≥ 1 := by\n                          omega\n                        omega\n                      have h₁₁ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) ≥ 2 ^ 3 := by\n                        exact pow_le_pow_right (by norm_num) (by omega)\n                      omega\n                    omega\n                  -- Use the fact that both numbers are congruent to 2 modulo 3 to show they are coprime\n                  have h₉ : Nat.gcd (2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) (2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) = 1 := by\n                    have h₁₀ : ∀ a b : ℕ, a > 0 → b > 0 → (a % 3 = 2) → (b % 3 = 2) → Nat.gcd a b = 1 := by\n                      intro a b ha hb ha' hb'\n                      have h₁₁ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ a := Nat.gcd_dvd_left a b\n                      have h₁₂ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ b := Nat.gcd_dvd_right a b\n                      have h₁₃ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ 3 := by\n                        have h₁₄ : a % 3 = 2 := ha'\n                        have h₁₅ : b % 3 = 2 := hb'\n                        have h₁₆ : (a - b) % 3 = 0 := by\n                          omega\n                        have h₁₇ : 3 ∣ (a - b) := by\n                          omega\n                        have h₁₈ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ (a - b) := Nat.dvd_trans (Nat.gcd_dvd_left a b) (by\n                          simpa [Nat.dvd_sub'] using h₁₇)\n                        have h₁₉ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ 3 := by\n                          have h₂₀ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ a := Nat.gcd_dvd_left a b\n                          have h₂₁ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ b := Nat.gcd_dvd_right a b\n                          have h₂₂ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ (a - b) := h₁₈\n                          have h₂₃ : Nat.gcd a b ∣ 3 := by\n                            -- Use the fact that if a number divides both a and b, it must divide any linear combination of a and b\n                            have h₂₄ : a % 3 = 2 := ha'\n                            have h₂₅ : b % 3 = 2 := hb'\n                            have h₂₆ : (a - b) % 3 = 0 := by omega\n                            omega\n                          exact h₂₃\n                        exact h₁₉\n                      have h₂₀ : Nat.gcd a b ≤ 3 := Nat.le_of_dvd (by decide) h₁₃\n                      interval_cases Nat.gcd a b <;> norm_num at h₁₁ h₁₂ ⊢ <;>\n                        (try omega) <;>\n                        (try {\n                          have h₂₁ : a % 3 = 2 := ha'\n                          have h₂₂ : b % 3 = 2 := hb'\n                          omega\n                        }) <;>\n                        (try {\n                          omega\n                        })\n                    have h₁₁ : (2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) % 3 = 2 := by\n                      omega\n                    have h₁₂ : (2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3) % 3 = 2 := by\n                      omega\n                    have h₁₃ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) - 3 > 0 := by\n                      have h₁₄ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) > 3 := by\n                        have h₁₅ : 2 * n + 1 ≥ 3 := by\n                          have h₁₆ : n ≥ 1 := by\n                            omega\n                          omega\n                        have h₁₇ : 2 ^ ((2 * n + 1 : ℕ)) ≥ 2 ^ 3 := by\n                          exact pow_le_pow_right (by norm_num) (by omega)\n                        omega\n                      omega\n                    have h₁₄ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) - 3 > 0 := by\n                      have h₁₅ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) > 3 := by\n                        have h₁₆ : 2 * m + 1 ≥ 3 := by\n                          have h₁₇ : m ≥ 1 := by\n                            omega\n                          omega\n                        have h₁₈ : 2 ^ ((2 * m + 1 : ℕ)) ≥ 2 ^ 3 := by\n                          exact pow_le